The defendant Jameerah Rosa Morgan was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Jameerah Rosa Morgan is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Jameerah Rosa Morgan was found guilty of Forgery-Uttering [Modifiers: Conspiracy], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.38(2).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Order amending judgment of conviction; signed and filed.
Pursuant to Sec 973.01, WI Stats. JAMEERAH R. MORGAN (DOB. 02-21-1985)  was sentenced to a bifurcated sentence.
Pursuant to Sec. 302.05(3)(c), WI Stats., within 30 days after the court has been notified that the defendant has successfully completed the Earned Release Program, the court shall modify the bifurcated sentence.  The portion of the Confinement Time not served will be added to the Extended Supervision portion of the sentence.  The total length of the sentence will not change.
Whereas, JAMEERAH R. MORGAN entered and began participation in the Earned Release Program on 07-16-2018.
Whereas, JAMEERAH R. MORGAN has successfully completed the Earned Release Program of 10-05-2018.
It is ordered that the Department of Corrections will effectuate the change from Confinement to Extended Supervision upon receipt of this order, determining the actual number of days served in Confinement and changing the remaining Confinement to Extended Supervision.  The number of days that are converted from Confinement Time to Extended Supervision will be determined by DOC Central Records, and will be based upon actual release date.
It is further ordered that the Warden/Superintendent of the institution to which the prisoner is assigned shall effect his or her release upon receipt of this order.
In all other respects, the original judgment herein is affirmed.
Paperwork forwarded to the Clerk of Court's Office to amend the judgment of conviction.
DOC is requesting the Court to authorize the inmate's release and conversion of remaining confinement time to extended supervision.  Assigned to Br. 18, Judge Colon.  jm

records.addlTxt:
Defendant prepared to enter change of plea.  Hearing proceeded.  Negotiations set forth by the state.

As to Count 1 and Count 3 as amended:  The defendant was advised of her constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Addendum to Plea Questionnaire, and Jury Instructions received and filed.  The parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  The Court found the defendant guilty and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.  

As to Count 2:  Pursuant to plea negotiations and on State's motion, the court orders Count 2 DISMISSED but read-in for sentencing purposes. 

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by parties. 

As to Count 1:  The court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM term in the Wisconsin State Prison of 5 years, consecutive to Count 3, credit for 125 days time served, the term of INITIAL CONFINEMENT is 2 years, the term of EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 3 years. 

As to Count 3:  The court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM term in the Wisconsin State Prison of 5 years, consecutive to Count 1, the term of INITIAL CONFINEMENT is 2 years, the term of EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 3 years.

Court finds defendant is eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program after serving 2 years of initial confinement.  Court does not find the defendant eligible for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION: 
- DNA sample. 
- Restitution set as follows: $10,645.31 payable to BMO Harris, $4,678.45 payable to Associated Bank, $6,413.19 payable to Capitol CU, $2,850.00 payable to Baylake Bank, $2,803.80 payable to Bank Mutual, $1,093.07 payable to Johnson Bank, $3,205.60 payable to TCF Bank, $3,914.64 payable to Waterstone Bank.  Total restitution of $35,604.06 is to be paid joint and several with co-defendants Curtis Caffey, Latoya Jennings, Bradley Wallace, Bradley Boswell.  Restitution to be collected by DOC from the defendant's wages and from other monies held in the defendant's inmate account; an amount or percentage which the department determines is reasonable for restitution to victims; balance to be paid during extended supervision; nonpayment penalty shall be a civil judgment.
- Pay all costs, fees and surcharges, to be collected by DOC from defendant's wages and from other monies held in the defendant's inmate account; an amount or a percentage which the department determines is reasonable; balance to be paid during extended supervision; nonpayment penalty shall be a civil judgment.

Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon she may never possess a firearm. Court advised defendant that her voting rights are suspended and she may not vote in any election until her civil rights are restored. Court advised defendant of her right to seek postconviction relief.

Filed: Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief, Pretrial Incarceration Credit, Ineligible Voting Notice and Acknowledgment, Written Explanation of Determinate Sentence.
